          <p class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-900">Same Day</p>
          <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Service in Athens</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-900">Limestone</p>
          <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">County Coverage</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-900">27,000+</p>
          <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Athens Residents</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-900">Free</p>
          <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Estimates Always</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- About Athens Section -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-gray-50">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-4">
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-center">
        <div>
          <span
            class="text-orange-500 font-semibold text-sm uppercase tracking-wide"
            >Limestone County's Heart</span
          >
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-800 mt-2 mb-6">
            Serving Historic Athens & Limestone County
          </h2>
          <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
            Athens holds a special place in Alabama history. Founded in 1818,
            it's one of the state's oldest cities, with a beautifully preserved
            courthouse square and historic neighborhoods that reflect nearly two
            centuries of Southern heritage. Home to Athens State University
            since 1822, the city blends small-town charm with educational
            excellence.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
            Today, Athens is growing as families discover its excellent schools,
            affordable housing, and easy commute to Huntsville and Decatur. New
            subdivisions are sprouting alongside historic farmsteads, creating
            diverse housing stock that ranges from antebellum homes to modern
            construction.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-600">
            Based just 25 minutes away in Madison, we serve all of Athens and
            Limestone County with the same quality and reliability we're known
            for. Whether you have a historic home needing careful restoration or
            new construction requiring finishing touches, we treat every Athens
            home with the care it deserves.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-blue-900 mb-4">
            Athens Quick Facts
          </h3>
          <ul class="space-y-3">
            {
              athensHistory.map((fact) => (
                <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                  <svg
                    class="w-5 h-5 text-green-500 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"
                    fill="none"
                    stroke="currentColor"
                    viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  >
                    <path
                      stroke-linecap="round"
                      stroke-linejoin="round"
                      stroke-width="2"
                      d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"
                    />
                  </svg>
                  <span class="text-gray-700">{fact}</span>
                </li>
              ))
            }
          </ul>
          <div class="mt-6 pt-4 border-t border-gray-200">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-2">
              Why Athens Residents Choose Us
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
              Athens homeowners value reliability, fair pricing, and contractors
              who show up when they say they will. We've built our Athens client
              base through referrals from satisfied customers who appreciate
              honest work at honest prices.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Elevated Direct Response: Athens Home Investment -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4">
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-8">
          What Athens Homeowners Should Know About Protecting Their Property
          Value
        </h2>
        <p>
          Athens occupies a unique position in North Alabama's real estate
          landscape. It offers something that Madison and Huntsville
          increasingly cannot: genuine small-town character with legitimate
          access to major employment centers. A house in Athens is not simply
          shelter. It is an entry point into a community where your neighbor
          knows your name, your children walk to friends' houses, and the pace
          of life allows you to actually enjoy the property you have invested
          in. That community dimension adds real value—but only if the house
          itself reflects the care that the neighborhood expects.
        </p>
        <p>
          In a city where reputation travels by word of mouth rather than
          algorithm, the condition of your home communicates something about
          you. A freshly painted exterior with clean gutters and tight trim
          tells the neighborhood that you are invested in this place. Peeling
          soffits and sagging porch boards communicate the opposite. This is not
          vanity. In Athens, where property values are climbing as Huntsville
          commuters discover the quality of life here, deferred maintenance
          quietly erodes the equity you have been building.
        </p>
        <p>
          The housing stock in Limestone County spans a remarkable range.
          Downtown Athens contains structures that predate the Civil War—homes
          with plaster walls, heart pine floors, and architectural detailing
          that cannot be replicated at any price. These homes demand a craftsman
          who understands that repair means restoration, not replacement. A few
          miles out on Nick Davis Road, brand-new subdivisions are rising from
          former cotton fields, their homes built to modern code but not yet
          tested by Alabama's punishing seasonal cycles. Between those extremes
          sits the majority of Athens housing: well-built homes from the 1970s
          through the 2000s that need thoughtful, systematic maintenance to
          remain comfortable, efficient, and structurally sound.
        </p>
        <p>
          We approach Athens with particular respect for how this community
          operates. When a teacher at Athens City Schools recommends us to a
          colleague, that recommendation carries weight precisely because it was
          earned, not solicited. When a nurse at Athens-Limestone Hospital tells
          a neighbor about the drywall work we completed during her night-shift
          schedule, that referral matters because it came from genuine
          experience. We do not spend money on billboard advertising in Athens.
          We invest that energy instead into making sure every single job we
          complete there generates the kind of result that compels the homeowner
          to mention us at church, at the Little League field, or across the
          back fence.
        </p>
        <p>
          The practical reality is straightforward: Athens homes face the same
          climate pressures as the rest of North Alabama—severe spring storms,
          brutally humid summers, heavy fall leaf loads, and occasional winter
          ice events—but many Athens properties also contend with the additional
          challenges of larger lots, mature hardwood canopy, and older
          construction techniques that modern contractors may not recognize. We
          recognize all of it. We have worked on historic plaster, on homes with
          original wood siding, and on properties where the trees are older than
          the house. Limestone County deserves a contractor who approaches each
          project with the same attention to detail that the community brings to
          everything else it values.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Neighborhoods Section -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-4">
      <div class="text-center mb-12">
        <span
